      modelAnswer: 'As an organism becomes larger, its volume increases as the cube of its linear dimension while its surface area increases only as the square. The surface area to volume ratio (SA:V) therefore falls. Single-celled and small organisms have high SA:V and rely on simple diffusion across the body surface for gas exchange and nutrient uptake; metabolic demand is met because diffusion distances are short. As size increases, diffusion alone cannot meet demand: oxygen would never reach interior cells in time. Large organisms have therefore evolved specialised exchange surfaces and mass transport systems. Mammalian lungs contain millions of alveoli, giving an enormous surface area, thin walls (single squamous cells), a moist surface and a rich blood supply that maintains the diffusion gradient by ventilation and circulation. Fish use gills with countercurrent flow, where blood flows opposite to water, maintaining a gradient along the entire gill lamella and extracting up to 80% of dissolved oxygen. Insects use a tracheal system that delivers air directly to tissues. Mass transport is essential because diffusion is too slow over long distances: in mammals the heart pumps oxygenated blood through arteries to capillaries close to every cell, and in flowering plants xylem carries water up the stem by transpiration pull. Without these adaptations, large multicellular life would not be possible.'
