      modelAnswer: 'The light-dependent reactions occur in the thylakoid membranes of chloroplasts. Light is absorbed by chlorophyll in photosystem II, exciting electrons that pass down an electron transport chain. As electrons flow, energy is used to pump protons (H⁺) from the stroma into the thylakoid lumen, generating a proton gradient. Protons flow back through ATP synthase, producing ATP (photophosphorylation). Electrons lost from photosystem II are replaced by photolysis of water: 2H₂O → 4H⁺ + 4e⁻ + O₂; this releases the O₂ given off as a waste product. Electrons reach photosystem I and are re-energised by light, then accepted by NADP along with H⁺ to form reduced NADP (NADPH). The net products are ATP, NADPH and O₂. ATP and NADPH are used in the light-independent (Calvin) reactions in the stroma. Carbon dioxide combines with ribulose bisphosphate (RuBP, 5C) catalysed by RuBisCO to form two molecules of glycerate 3-phosphate (GP, 3C). GP is reduced to triose phosphate (TP) using ATP and NADPH from the light-dependent reactions. Most TP is used to regenerate RuBP (using more ATP), while some leaves the cycle and is used to synthesise glucose, amino acids, lipids and other organic compounds. Without ATP and NADPH from the light-dependent stage, the Calvin cycle would stop, demonstrating how the two stages are coupled.'
