      modelAnswer: 'Negative feedback is a control mechanism in which a deviation from a set point triggers responses that reverse the change, returning the system to the set point. It is the foundation of homeostasis because it produces stability without rigid control: any small departure is detected by receptors, processed by a control centre and corrected by effectors. In temperature regulation, hypothalamic thermoreceptors detect blood temperature; if too high, sweating, vasodilation and reduced metabolic rate cool the body; if too low, shivering, vasoconstriction, raised metabolic rate (and in some animals piloerection or brown fat thermogenesis) raise temperature. The result is a body temperature held within a narrow range (~36.5–37.5 °C) despite environmental change, allowing enzymes to function near optimum. In water balance, osmoreceptors in the hypothalamus detect blood water potential. If water potential is low, ADH is released from the posterior pituitary, increasing aquaporin insertion in the collecting duct walls, more water is reabsorbed and a small volume of concentrated urine is produced; if water potential is high, ADH falls and a larger volume of dilute urine is excreted. Strengths of negative feedback include continuous, sensitive correction and the ability to handle multiple variables simultaneously; its limitation is that it always lags behind the disturbance and corrects rather than prevents change. Positive feedback (e.g. in childbirth, action potentials) drives change rapidly to completion but is unstable; the body uses it sparingly. Overall, negative feedback is the dominant mechanism that keeps internal conditions optimal, but it works alongside other regulatory strategies to maintain life.'
