      modelAnswer: 'Natural selection acts on phenotypic variation within a population. Directional selection favours individuals at one extreme of the phenotypic range, shifting the population mean over time. A classic example is peppered moths in industrial Britain, where dark forms became more common as soot-blackened tree bark reduced the survival of light forms; when pollution decreased, selection reversed. Antibiotic-resistant bacteria are another example. Stabilising selection favours intermediate phenotypes and selects against both extremes, reducing variation and keeping the mean stable. Birth weight in humans is the textbook case: very low and very high birth weights are associated with greater infant mortality, so the mean has remained near 3.5 kg for many generations. Disruptive selection favours both extremes and selects against the mean, increasing variation and potentially leading to two distinct subpopulations and (if reproductive isolation follows) sympatric speciation. An example is bill size in some Galápagos finches, where the most efficient bill sizes for cracking either large hard seeds or small soft seeds are favoured, but intermediate bills are inefficient at both. Directional selection produces adaptation and change; stabilising selection conserves a successful phenotype; disruptive selection drives diversification. All three rely on heritable variation and differences in survival and reproduction, but they act on different parts of the phenotypic distribution.'
