      modelAnswer: 'A totipotent cell is one that can give rise to all cell types of the organism, including extra-embryonic tissues. The zygote and early embryonic cells are totipotent. As the embryo develops, cells divide and differentiate: chemical signals trigger different sets of genes to be expressed and others to be repressed, often via methylation and histone modification. Cells become pluripotent (can form any cell type but not extra-embryonic tissues), then multipotent (can form a limited range of related cell types, e.g. blood-cell lineages from bone marrow stem cells), then unipotent or fully differentiated (only one cell type). Differentiation involves stable changes in gene expression rather than gene loss — almost every cell still contains the full genome. Adult tissues retain pools of multipotent stem cells (e.g. in bone marrow, skin, gut epithelium) that can replenish lost cells. Medical uses of stem cells include treatment of leukaemia by bone marrow transplant (existing therapy), regeneration of skin for burns patients, growing organs for transplantation, treating Parkinson\'s by replacing dopaminergic neurones, restoring sight by replacing retinal cells, and repairing spinal cord damage. Embryonic stem cells are pluripotent and have great potential but raise ethical concerns because their use destroys an embryo. Induced pluripotent stem (iPS) cells are made by reprogramming adult cells (e.g. skin fibroblasts) using transcription factors such as OCT4, SOX2, KLF4 and MYC, providing pluripotent cells without embryos and with patient-matched genetics, reducing rejection. Challenges include ensuring stem cells differentiate fully and do not form tumours, scaling up production, and avoiding immune rejection. With these issues addressed, stem cell therapy could revolutionise the treatment of many degenerative diseases and injuries.'
