      modelAnswer: 'A gene mutation is a change in the DNA base sequence within a gene. Substitutions replace one base with another and may be silent (no change in amino acid because of code redundancy), missense (different amino acid) or nonsense (premature stop codon). Insertions or deletions cause frameshifts that change every codon downstream and almost always lead to a non-functional protein. Chromosomal mutations are larger-scale changes affecting whole chromosomes or chunks of them: deletion (loss of a section), inversion (reversed section), duplication (extra copy) and translocation (section moved to a different chromosome). Aneuploidy is a change in chromosome number such as trisomy 21 (Down syndrome). Both types arise from errors in DNA replication or segregation, often increased by mutagens (UV light, ionising radiation, chemicals such as benzene). Cancer is a disease of uncontrolled cell division caused by accumulating mutations. Mutations in proto-oncogenes (e.g. RAS, MYC) can convert them to oncogenes, producing constitutively active proteins that drive cell division. Mutations or epigenetic silencing of tumour suppressor genes (e.g. TP53, RB) remove the brakes on the cell cycle and the apoptosis that should otherwise eliminate damaged cells. Mutations in DNA repair genes (e.g. BRCA1) increase the rate at which further mutations occur. Typically, several such mutations are needed for a cell to become cancerous (multiple-hit hypothesis), which is why cancer risk increases with age. Inherited mutations (e.g. BRCA1, APC) predispose individuals but require additional somatic mutations to cause disease. Gene mutations and chromosomal mutations therefore both feed into carcinogenesis, and identifying the specific mutations in a tumour now guides targeted therapies.'
